MELPe 2400bps must be used as codec for the IP voice stream and they must be included in the RTP payload according to RFC 8130
The IOP-HD shall use VARC-based half-duplex PTT control
The destination address of the voice packets must be IPv4
The identified voice stream must be mapped to the internal PTT voice service of the radio
Each voice group must be backed by a specific voice channel of the radio
Destination addresses for the received voice stream for each voice group within the radio must be configured statically according to national considerations as part of the voice group configuration.
Pre-emption of voice streams must be based on the source IP-address and/or the QoS marking of the IP-packets containing the respective voice stream.
Each voice group within the radios must be addressed via a combination of IP address, UDP port.
A radio as well as a client / intercom must accept any number of MELPe frames in a single RTP packet. The size of an RTP packet must never exceed the MTU of an IP packet.
The Radio IP Access function must either be embedded on the same radio device or via an external adapter.
Each platform must not have more than one active radio channel/line per radio network.
Every radio of the relay platform taking part in the relay functionality must be be configured with the same IPv4 multicast address and port of the Tactical Voice Service
Relaying must not be performed between more than two radio networks
There must not be more than one platform acting as relay between two particular radio networks
When a PTT button at a radio is pressed, the radio must also send the the voice stream onto the platform network (to the local client / intercom and the other radio).

sreqName: Indirect Fire Support Service port range shall be 6411-6417. Default value is 6413.
ASCA/CTIDP message shall be labelled with classification.

ASCA Gateways shall filter ASCA/CTIDP messages and only permit ASCA/CTIDP interactions by known/configured IP adresses and NATO Aliases.

Note: this requirement mainly applies to the application stack that processes ASCA/CTIDP messages; it does not imply that ASCA gateways are single-tasking: depending on national choices, a software ASCA gateway can be integrated into a multi-service network gateway.
ASCA Gateways must log security events.

Network Interconnection Points (NIPs) shall be locally provided to enable interconnections between ASCA Gateways on different national extensions, for each federated Joint Fire Support Elements (f-JFSE) or multinational Artillery Command Posts over the Coalition Deployment.

To decide the number and location of f-JFSEs or multinational Artillery Command Posts, the Task Organization of the multinational Force, especially related to the Artillery and Fire Support deployment, has precedence to any technical consideration, even regarding possible optimized coalition network topology.
ASCA Gateways shall perform technical coherency checks on ASCA/CTIDP messages.

ASCA Gateways interconnected through ''Kinetic Indirect Fire Support'' technical interaction (TIN-318) shall be simultaneously connected to their national Fire Control chain in order to provide an end-to-end digital sensor-to-shooter kill chain.
